WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:29.000
[Amit Varma]: There is an old quote often attributed to Horace Walpole

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
[Amit Varma]: The world is a tragedy to those who feel and a comedy to those who think.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, often the best way to deal with difficulty or sadness is through humour.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
[Amit Varma]: And the best comedy is always much more than merely funny.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: It's no surprise then that a society can be at its funniest when things look really bleak.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Soviet humour was renowned during the dark communist years of the Soviet Union.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:01.000
[Amit Varma]: There was no other way to cope and the only alternative to a hearty laugh was to descend into a deep never-ending funk.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And for those of us who believe that Indian society and Indian democracy is going through a difficult phase,

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: it's no surprise that the quality of our humour is getting better and better.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Because when things get so bleak that they are no laughing matter, that's when they are indeed a laughing matter.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:27.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural science.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
[Amit Varma]: When stand-up comedy first came to India, it was shallow and derivative,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.000
[Amit Varma]: performed by privileged kids who lacked life experience and an understanding of what India was really all about.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:44.000
[Amit Varma]: That has changed.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
[Amit Varma]: The best stand-up comics in India today are both deeply self-aware and engaging with the world around them,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
[Amit Varma]: feeding off it and feeding into it.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
[Amit Varma]: To discuss the evolution of both comedy in general and stand-up comedy in particular,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
[Amit Varma]: I have invited Aditi Mittal onto the show.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Aditi needs no introduction from me.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Google her, see her videos on YouTube, browse her YouTube channel especially I recommend

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.000
[Amit Varma]: and you'll get a sense of what she's all about.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Also, the producer of The Scene and The Unseen, Abbas Momin, also happens to be a stand-up comic.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:21.000
[Amit Varma]: So I asked him to sit in as a guest and co-host with me and come in front of the mic for once.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
[Amit Varma]: For what it's worth, I wanted to record two episodes with Aditi.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:31.000
[Amit Varma]: I wanted one whole episode on the subject of misogyny in entertainment and in Indian society.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
[Amit Varma]: But that'll be the next episode.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.000
[Amit Varma]: In this one, we'll talk more about the comedy scene in India than just this aspect of it.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:40.000
[Amit Varma]: But first, let's take a small break.

