00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
[Guest 1]: So that, you know, I always assume...

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:10.000
[Guest 1]: Long walks on the beach, dogs, candlelight dinners and dinners at candlelight dogs.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
[Guest 1]: Those are my preferences.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Okay, I'll take a few moments to fathom that.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:23.000
[Amit Varma]: But in this case, actually, there's a natural segue from sort of your personal journey

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.000
[Amit Varma]: to the subject of today's episode, which is, you know,

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
[Amit Varma]: the history of stand-up comedy and comedy in general,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
[Amit Varma]: which you have a lot of thoughts and feelings on.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So tell us a little bit about yourself.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, what did the eight-year-old Aditi want to be?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, how did the eight-year-old Aditi get here?

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
[Guest 1]: You know, the eight-year-old Aditi wanted to be a rickshaw driver

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Guest 1]: because I was just fascinated.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
[Guest 1]: I was like, oh my God, you get to go places and people will pay you.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
[Unknown]: And I just thought it was genius.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
[Guest 1]: I was like, oh my God, it's the whole day with the wind in your hair.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
[Guest 1]: And a meter on your shoulder.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.000
[Guest 1]: And a meter on your shoulder.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
[Guest 1]: I thought it was the ultimate sort of like, I would feel very jaunty if I was a rickshaw driver.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:09.000
[Guest 1]: And then I think I sort of grew out of that ambition.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest 1]: And then, you know, I think I wanted to be an elephant.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Guest 1]: That was my childhood aim, which I think I achieved.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
[Amit Varma]: You're giving your stand-up routine now. Come, come, come.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Shed the mask, show us the real Aditi.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:29.000
[Guest 1]: So I wanted to be a nun.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
[Guest 1]: No, I wanted to be, I don't know.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
[Amit Varma]: You didn't have wanted to be anything per se.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:37.000
[Amit Varma]: No particular aims.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But as you went through school and college and all that, you know, what were you studying?

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
[Amit Varma]: What were you looking at? What kind of person were you?

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Were you always funny?

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:50.000
[Guest 1]: I think, yeah, I don't know if I was always funny, but surely I was a nautanki.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
[Guest 1]: Like I was that kid, you know, when your relatives come over

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
[Guest 1]: and your parents say, dance for uncle and auntie.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
[Guest 1]: I was that kid who was like, which genre?

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.000
[Unknown]: I have a sad song, a happy song and I know that love is by heart.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And did they ever call you a bluff and say, dance for a year?

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.000
[Guest 1]: I would make it up. I would make it up on the spot.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And they wouldn't know because you're Indian uncles.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
[Guest 1]: Yes, they would just clap along politely.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
[Guest 1]: Like to the point that when my dad owed people money, he used to just call them home.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
[Guest 1]: They never came back.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
[Guest 1]: Because they were like, let it be, a kid from Mittal will have to see a six-hour show.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
[Guest 1]: So, too much stress.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
[Amit Varma]: My God, the loan collector's daughter.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Amit Varma]: So, Abbas, I got to give you some trivia that I found out about her before the show.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.000
[Unknown]: What is it?

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Both of us went to school in Pune.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And I studied in this place called Bishop's School.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And many years after me, of course, she studied in this neighboring school called St. Mary's.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And Bishop's was a boys' school, St. Mary's was a girls' school.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And Bishop's and Mary's used to have a social every year,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.000
[Amit Varma]: where boys and girls would get together.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And I don't know what the girls would think, but the boys would, like, the only social I went to,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
[Amit Varma]: I didn't talk to any girl because I was too scared.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
[Amit Varma]: I found the guitarist of the band and asked him for tips on how to play the guitar,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
[Amit Varma]: which I still don't know, by the way.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:07.000
[Amit Varma]: So, Aditi told me that she was like the school marmie presence among the girls.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And she would make sure that none of them, you know, danced with any of the boys or held hands with them or whatever.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
[Guest 1]: She was that kind of person.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
[Guest 1]: I've been preventing people from getting laid for like decades now.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:22.000
[Guest 1]: I think, yeah, but it's true.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest 1]: And our schools, by the way, Abbas was separated by one single wall.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
[Guest 1]: There was one single wall in between.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:31.000
[Guest 2]: It's like Israel and Palestine.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:39.000
[Guest 2]: It was, I mean, not as tragic, clearly, or fraught with sexual tension as our girls' schools and boys' schools.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.000
[Guest 2]: But yes.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
[Guest 2]: Nobody tried to climb over the walls or anything?

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest 1]: I was one of the, sort of, as I said, the asexual moms.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
[Unknown]: It would be like, sister, sister, someone is trying to go on the wall.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
[Unknown]: Sister, sister, I saw that one staring at that one.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
[Guest 1]: Just saying, I was a very popular kid among the teachers.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest 1]: Sisters.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, not so much among the girls.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Amit Varma]: So, after your early school career as a spoilsport and messing with everyone's fun, where did you go for college?

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
[Guest 1]: I went to Sophia College in Bombay.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
[Amit Varma]: A girls' college after a girls' school.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Now we know why you're so twisted.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:22.000
[Guest 1]: Actually, I think, you know, one of the advantages of being in an all-girls environment for me personally

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:26.000
[Guest 1]: has been the fact that whenever you're in a co-ed environment, the class clown would always be a guy.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[Guest 1]: You know, because any sort of clownish behavior from girls was never rewarded with laughs.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
[Guest 2]: It was always like, what are you doing? Are you crazy?

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.000
[Guest 1]: And I think with the fact that I was in an all-girls environment till very later on.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So you were the class jester?

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:47.000
[Guest 1]: Yes, I was sort of the one who would like raise my hand and give a smart-ass answer.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest 1]: Like 80% of my school life was spent kneeling outside class, just waiting for the break bell to ring

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest 1]: so that I could be the first one in the canteen for the samosas before they got over.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
[Guest 1]: But yeah, I think it really helped.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:09.000
[Guest 1]: It really helped to be in an environment where there was a constant also reinforcement of the things that women found funny.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:14.000
[Guest 1]: And I think, so if anyone, if you want to blame anyone for my career, it's them.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Amit Varma]: So that's where your bad carbohydrate habits started.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
[Amit Varma]: First one to the samosas, it seems.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:19.000
[Unknown]: But that's really interesting.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:25.000
[Amit Varma]: So what you mean is if you were in a normal, not a normal, but say a co-ed environment where there were both boys and girls,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
[Amit Varma]: you may not ever really have had the confidence to, you're saying, express your comedy and find your voice.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest 1]: Oh, clearly, clearly. 100%.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:43.000
[Guest 1]: And, you know, I know that the conversation about single sex environments in schools is a sort of, is very important to have.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
[Guest 1]: But I think that in this particular aspect, it really helped.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest 1]: It really helped.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:11:00.000
[Guest 1]: It made sort of, actually, going back, I met my first non-relative man when I was 19.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
[Guest 1]: And like met as in like interacted.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
[Guest 1]: And I remember being blown away that I was like, oh, my God, they have hair on their neck.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
[Guest 1]: You know, they smell like this in this one particular way. Their toes have hair on them.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:21.000
[Guest 1]: I just remember being sort of blown away by the male form at the age of 19, which I think was still kind of late in the day.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:27.000
[Guest 1]: But I think the natural shut ups that could have come to me till I was 19 didn't come.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
[Amit Varma]: What do you mean the natural shut ups?

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Oh, people saying shut up to you.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:37.000
[Guest 1]: Enough people telling you to shut up or policing you into a confined gender role that no, no, no, girls don't behave like this.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
[Guest 1]: Or women don't behave like this.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:47.000
[Guest 1]: We were able to sort of occupy more roles than just the prescribed act out of the gender that you are supposed to be.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And did that change after you left at all girls environment?

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:52.000
[Amit Varma]: Did you have to adjust?

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I was I was genuinely confused.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Guest 1]: I was genuinely sort of like frazzled and taken aback, sort of.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.000
[Guest 1]: But I think it helped also, again, in that way that I was very, I was a little bit too self-assured.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:16.000
[Guest 1]: When I was placed then in an environment where there were men as well, is that I was like, no, I know, I know that I am sort of my voice is worth listening to.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Guest 1]: I, the things I am saying are not like, oh no, no, just our talking.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest 1]: I just, I felt I had my sense of validation from within.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:32.000
[Guest 1]: So then by the time I went out into a world where there were all sorts of genders, I was more confident.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And we will talk about, you know, more about being a woman in this kind of an environment in sort of the next episode.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:50.000
[Amit Varma]: But just to kind of continue with that, you know, whenever I would go to a bookstore and there would be a section called humor and there would be books there and I would be like, humor is a part of everything.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
[Amit Varma]: It makes no sense to have a section which is called humor.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And so, OK, obviously, then as a schoolgirl and, you know, as a college going person, you are someone who's naturally funny and you're making your voice cracks and you're sort of, that's what you do.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:15.000
[Amit Varma]: At what point did you become aware of comedy as a genre by itself, which you could consume and which had value and be as something that you could do?

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:23.000
[Guest 1]: So, A, I think it was because, you know, my family is like my dad was hilarious.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:28.000
[Guest 1]: My dad was the funniest guy I ever knew. He I think he brought us up sarcastically.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.000
[Guest 1]: Like he brought us up. Like I remember there was he used to have this back scratcher.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
[Guest 1]: OK, and back scratchers were a rare commodity at some point.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.000
[Guest 1]: So I was totally fascinated with it. And one day I was chatting with him. I was just banging the back scratcher on the table.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest 1]: I was like, thug, thug, thug, thug, the papa, something, something. He looks at me and he's like, Aditi, what's going on? Why are you doing that?

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:55.000
[Guest 1]: I said, no, I say, ha ha ha, he's like, do me a favor. If you want to break it, at least hit it hard enough.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:01.000
[Guest 1]: And I stood there. I was so confused for a second. I was like, wait, should I hit it or not? I don't know.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:07.000
[Guest 1]: But he sort of was a very clever and very like he I think. But did you break it?

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
[Guest 1]: You know, ultimately I did.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:09.400
[Guest 1]: Ultimately I did.

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:10.520
[Unknown]: Five years later.

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:11.200
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:13.800
[Guest 1]: But I mean, that backstab had a long life.

00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:15.520
[Guest 1]: Thanks to that one sarcastic comment.

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:21.760
[Guest 1]: Um, and he sort of attributed a lot more intelligence to us than I think we had, to

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:22.680
[Amit Varma]: be very honest.

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:24.440
[Amit Varma]: And did that make you more intelligent?

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And I'm asking that seriously.

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:27.960
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:32.880
[Guest 1]: Cause you, I really, I did want to sort of, whenever he put an expectation in front of

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:34.080
[Guest 1]: me, I wanted to fulfill it.

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:37.720
[Guest 1]: I think one of the main functions of humor is to dispel tension.

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:44.000
[Guest 1]: And, um, I sort of had a, I had a fairly unconventional life, uh, you know, not from

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:45.800
[Guest 1]: just the general nuclear or joint family.

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:50.920
[Guest 1]: Um, so we constantly found ourselves in situations with a lot of adults and

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:53.200
[Guest 1]: slightly tense situations.

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:57.840
[Guest 1]: And I realized the only way out of it was to make a joke about it or to sort of do a

00:14:57.840 --> 00:14:59.400
[Guest 1]: silly dance or something like that.

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:03.800
[Guest 1]: And I realized that would dispel the tension and make me more acceptable to sit

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:07.960
[Guest 1]: around in the room long enough till it came time for me to crack the next joke or say

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:08.840
[Guest 1]: something silly again.

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:14.440
[Guest 1]: Um, and so just sort of became, it was a sort of a defense mechanism as well as a way

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:15.720
[Guest 1]: to appeal to people.

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:21.080
[Guest 1]: I switched schools when I was, uh, in ninth standard, uh, because the boarding school

00:15:21.080 --> 00:15:22.200
[Guest 1]: I was in, St. Mary's, sorry.

00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:24.440
[Guest 1]: Um, they shut down.

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:28.000
[Guest 1]: And so my father was like, oh, you have, we have to put you in another boarding school

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:29.560
[Guest 1]: and they took me to Panchkani.

00:15:30.200 --> 00:15:34.600
[Guest 1]: And I had had all these friends for me, you know, from like junior KG to eighth

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:34.920
[Guest 1]: standard.

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:37.880
[Guest 1]: And now suddenly I'm in this new school, ninth standard, tenth standard.

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:39.080
[Guest 1]: I was totally confused.

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:39.880
[Amit Varma]: Also a girls school.

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:40.280
[Guest 1]: Yes.

00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:47.000
[Guest 1]: Um, I remember that weekend when I was going to school, uh, Kaho Na Pyar Hai had

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:47.480
[Guest 1]: come out.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:50.120
[Guest 1]: That movie is my spirit animal.

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:52.120
[Guest 1]: Kaho Na Pyar Hai had come out.

00:15:52.120 --> 00:15:54.120
[Guest 1]: I memorized the entire movie.

00:15:55.080 --> 00:15:56.680
[Guest 1]: Every single word of that movie.

00:15:56.680 --> 00:15:58.120
[Amit Varma]: You saw it once or?

00:15:58.120 --> 00:16:00.200
[Guest 1]: Like maybe three times.

00:16:00.200 --> 00:16:02.200
[Guest 1]: On Monday.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:07.560
[Guest 1]: And, um, I memorized that entire movie, including like transitions, like the don't

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:08.920
[Guest 1]: ask me dad, I'm in love.

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:09.400
[Guest 1]: I'm in love.

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:10.440
[Guest 1]: Hey, I'm there.

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:14.200
[Guest 1]: Just song to dialogue, dialogue to song.

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:15.240
[Guest 1]: You remember it all now?

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:16.040
[Amit Varma]: Kind of.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:16.520
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:18.840
[Amit Varma]: Um, why did you do that?

00:16:19.720 --> 00:16:24.120
[Guest 1]: Cause the, the first day that I got into school, you know, all the other new girls

00:16:24.120 --> 00:16:26.760
[Guest 1]: was sort of unpacking and being sort of bummed out.

00:16:27.480 --> 00:16:32.840
[Guest 1]: I just put on my best performer's hat and I acted out the movie for like a bunch of

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:35.480
[Guest 1]: 10 standard girls who were just confused.

00:16:35.480 --> 00:16:36.920
[Guest 1]: They're like, who the f**k is this girl?

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:39.480
[Guest 1]: She's new here, but she's not crying.

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:41.080
[Guest 1]: She's sitting and doing don't ask me, dad.

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:41.720
[Guest 1]: I'm in love.

00:16:41.720 --> 00:16:42.360
[Guest 1]: I'm in love.

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:46.840
[Guest 1]: I, and I still have friends from that time who remember me for that.

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:50.920
[Guest 1]: Uh, well, I go, oh my God, you know, we became friends with Aditi because she just

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:52.600
[Guest 1]: was ridiculous and telling this story.

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:55.960
[Amit Varma]: And it's both very funny and in some way, very sad as well.

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:57.160
[Guest 1]: Oh, I think, yeah.

00:16:57.160 --> 00:17:01.320
[Guest 1]: Oh, I think in fact, one of the, I think comedy is one of the most deeply tragic things in

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:01.880
[Unknown]: the world.

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:02.360
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:17:02.600 --> 00:17:05.800
[Guest 1]: Um, it was sort of finding survival.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:11.880
[Guest 1]: It was finding a way to make yourself fit in, uh, that may not necessarily, uh, be about

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:14.520
[Guest 1]: asserting authority or asserting superiority.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:18.520
[Amit Varma]: Uh, finding empathy, which is hard for a new girl in a new school.

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:19.880
[Amit Varma]: So instead you do this.

00:17:19.880 --> 00:17:22.600
[Guest 1]: Yes, yes.

00:17:23.320 --> 00:17:30.760
[Guest 1]: Um, and also just the value of the funny person is, I mean, I love, I enjoy that mid range

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:35.160
[Guest 1]: where nobody cares who you are, but the moment you pipe up, they'll be like, they'll

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:36.600
[Guest 1]: acknowledge you and move on.

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:41.400
[Guest 1]: I love that, that, that temporary ability to hold someone's attention and have it gone

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:42.520
[Guest 1]: back.

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:45.480
[Guest 1]: Um, so yes, yes.

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:47.880
[Guest 1]: You know, it, it was about survival.

00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:53.960
[Guest 1]: It was, and as we discussed earlier, I think that comedy is sort of the other end of the

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:58.200
[Guest 1]: coin of every other emotion, whether it's fear, whether it's anger, whether it's sadness,

00:17:59.080 --> 00:18:02.760
[Guest 1]: whether it's humiliation, uh, everything plus time.

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:06.680
[Amit Varma]: So essentially what you're saying is you cope with every kind of anxiety by bringing

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:08.520
[Guest 1]: comedy into it and the spelling.

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:10.360
[Guest 1]: Oh yes, yes, surely.

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:16.200
[Guest 1]: In fact, one of the greatest examples of that, uh, is in, uh, uh, Johnny Leaver's new show,

00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:17.080
[Guest 1]: which he's doing right now.

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:18.520
[Guest 1]: It's a two hour special.

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:22.840
[Guest 1]: Uh, it is mind boggling that a 62 year old man is standing on stage for one and a half

00:18:22.840 --> 00:18:26.520
[Guest 1]: hours and sort of, you know, having at it with the audience.

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:32.200
[Guest 1]: And he, one of the bits he talks about is how, uh, you know, he had this drinking problem

00:18:32.200 --> 00:18:38.040
[Guest 1]: and then he gave it up and how everyone reacted to him giving up alcohol.

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:42.200
[Guest 1]: And that whole set is hilarious, that you know, that people are like, no, no.

00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:47.160
[Guest 1]: drink it. How did you leave it, etc. The offense that people feel when you say you've given up alcohol.

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:51.720
[Guest 1]: But just the fact that he was talking about something that was so deeply tragic.

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:57.560
[Guest 1]: I mean, his sort of addiction to alcohol is what led him to Christianity, which is the religion he

00:18:57.560 --> 00:19:02.840
[Guest 1]: practices right now and has brought a lot of stability to his life. But the fact that he was

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:10.280
[Guest 1]: able to channel something so profoundly tragic into just a room where 600 people were screaming.

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:14.280
[Guest 1]: And we were screaming at the back because we bought the cheap tickets at the back.

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:20.040
[Guest 1]: There were just people being like, Gio, Johnny, Gio. And I thought, where else would a story of

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:25.960
[Guest 1]: such utter vulnerability get these kind of just like air punching whoops.

00:19:25.960 --> 00:19:30.680
[Amit Varma]: And would you say that the best way to process such pain, such tragedy is comedy? It's the

00:19:30.680 --> 00:19:33.720
[Amit Varma]: only way. Otherwise you'll be crushed by the weight. Is that what?

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:40.120
[Guest 1]: Yes. Yes. I think in fact, comedy is one of the best ways to move on from something

00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:44.920
[Guest 1]: that you find tragic. They say that comedy is tragedy plus time.

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:46.840
[Guest 2]: Yeah. Beautiful quote.

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:54.920
[Guest 1]: So just adding time to what is so sad or so painful is what propels you to move on.

00:19:56.120 --> 00:20:01.240
[Guest 1]: Even that's why, have you by the way, I know we spoke about this earlier, but

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:04.200
[Guest 1]: Hannah Gadsby's new special Nanette, did you watch it?

00:20:04.200 --> 00:20:07.720
[Unknown]: I haven't watched it yet. Everybody's been recommending it to me.

00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:13.080
[Guest 1]: Oh my God, Abbas. Oh my God. So you must watch it. Oh, please Amit if you have the time.

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:19.240
[Guest 1]: But she sort of discusses that. She discusses how at the base of comedy,

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:24.120
[Guest 1]: every funny story you tell actually has something really sad in it.

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:29.480
[Guest 1]: And I can actually tell you my personal story that I decided to do on stage was,

00:20:29.480 --> 00:20:32.840
[Guest 1]: one day I asked my dad to drop me to the airport.

00:20:33.720 --> 00:20:38.120
[Guest 1]: And my dad was reading the newspaper. And so, you know, he puts away the newspaper.

00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:42.440
[Guest 1]: He's looking for his, you know, glasses. He goes, looks for the keys.

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:46.120
[Guest 1]: You know, he was sitting in his lungi. So he went and he changed into his pants.

00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:47.640
[Guest 1]: He opens the door and he's waiting there.

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:53.560
[Guest 1]: And because that generation, I think they're not used to airline travelers, we are.

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:56.360
[Guest 1]: He started getting anxious. He was like, get to the airport early.

00:20:56.360 --> 00:21:00.600
[Guest 1]: Get to the airport early. Just get to the airport. Like just get there before the Wright

00:21:00.600 --> 00:21:04.440
[Guest 1]: brothers invent the airplane. Just get there. I feel like you're talking about me.

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:09.640
[Unknown]: That generation, like, you know, I mean, yeah, I'm not, I'm not offended by it.

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:13.720
[Amit Varma]: And I will find a way to cope with the deep sadness I feel now in the due course of time.

00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:18.360
[Guest 1]: But he, and so he was getting really anxious.

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:21.960
[Guest 1]: And I was just sort of like goofing off. I was like, hey,

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:26.360
[Guest 1]: Papa, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick, lipstick,

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:32.920
[Guest 1]: and he got so angry. He slapped himself.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:39.960
[Guest 1]: That like, because I mean, he couldn't raise his hand on me because I was clearly a 30 year old

00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:43.160
[Guest 1]: woman who can't leave the house without being like Papa.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:49.240
[Guest 1]: And it's funny now. It's really funny now.

00:21:49.240 --> 00:21:51.880
[Guest 1]: But that moment, like, I think that was my reckoning.

00:21:51.880 --> 00:21:56.120
[Guest 1]: That was my moment when I was like, I can't be a child anymore.

00:21:56.920 --> 00:21:59.000
[Guest 1]: I think that was my big growing up moment.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:03.640
[Guest 1]: And I was sort of distraught about that incident for a very long time.

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:06.680
[Guest 1]: But I think I managed to find a funny way to tell it.

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:12.760
[Guest 1]: And it, I mean, of course, later on improved relations between me and my dad,

00:22:12.760 --> 00:22:16.280
[Guest 1]: you know, when I was like, Papa, I'm so sorry that I put you through this.

00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:19.800
[Guest 1]: And, and he was just like, you know, it's fine. It's, you know,

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:23.960
[Guest 1]: how we process things and how we grow up. And I mean, but that's not,

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:25.080
[Guest 1]: that's not an interesting punchline.

00:22:25.080 --> 00:22:26.360
[Amit Varma]: It's not an interesting punchline.

00:22:26.360 --> 00:22:29.000
[Amit Varma]: He was probably in the middle of solving a sudoku or something,

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:32.040
[Guest 1]: you know, disturb someone in the middle of that you are asking for trouble.

00:22:32.040 --> 00:22:33.240
[Guest 1]: He was doing a crossword.

00:22:33.240 --> 00:22:34.760
[Guest 1]: He was doing a crossword.

00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:37.560
[Amit Varma]: You go nailed it. I know what men are like.

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.840
[Guest 1]: So that's what like, but me saying that, you know, well,

00:22:41.480 --> 00:22:44.120
[Guest 1]: that my relationship between my dad improved is not a punchline.

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:47.080
[Guest 2]: Your dad saw you do that bit?

00:22:47.080 --> 00:22:47.480
[Guest 2]: No.

00:22:47.480 --> 00:22:48.280
[Guest 2]: Oh, he hasn't seen it.

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:52.680
[Guest 1]: Yeah. I mean, he passed away in July last year, so he didn't see a lot of the stuff.

00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:55.640
[Amit Varma]: But what did he think of your, I mean, when you,

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:59.800
[Guest 1]: It is astonishing, actually, that he thought, I mean, he was one of those,

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:05.400
[Guest 1]: he would sit in a comedy show, second row, tears running down his face because he's so proud.

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:11.240
[Guest 1]: I was like, Papa, that is not the desired reaction at the comedy show.

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:13.560
[Guest 2]: So, one, why is this man crying?

00:23:16.600 --> 00:23:18.920
[Amit Varma]: Because he gets to the essence of comedy strategy.

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:30.040
[Guest 1]: He was one of those that would like, sort of every show I did,

00:23:30.040 --> 00:23:35.320
[Guest 1]: he would be like, and then sometimes come and then sit at the back and pass out.

00:23:35.320 --> 00:23:40.360
[Guest 1]: And I'm like, Papa, you were sleeping? And he's like, oh, it was AC, it was nice and dark.

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:43.320
[Guest 1]: So, I heard it, so I was like, I lulled off.

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:45.880
[Guest 1]: I was like, why did you come? You could have sat at home.

00:23:45.880 --> 00:23:48.520
[Unknown]: No, no, I'll tell you guys, your generation also, your generation,

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:53.960
[Unknown]: you guys, you kids these days also take so many things for granted, including AC.

00:23:53.960 --> 00:23:56.680
[Unknown]: AC is such a big freaking deal.

00:23:56.680 --> 00:24:00.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, I remember when I was in college in Pune, Ferguson College, sweltering summer,

00:24:00.920 --> 00:24:04.920
[Amit Varma]: every afternoon I would go to the British Council library, sit for five, six hours.

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:07.320
[Amit Varma]: People would say, boy likes reading. It's AC.

00:24:08.120 --> 00:24:10.920
[Unknown]: It gave us this podcast. I think it all worked out.

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:14.040
[Unknown]: It all worked out in the end. You guys take AC for granted,

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:17.160
[Unknown]: GPS for granted. I see people taking. How can you?

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:21.320
[Guest 1]: Yeah, we do. So, he was super supportive.

00:24:21.320 --> 00:24:29.400
[Guest 1]: And my mom, you know, in spite of the fact that she also works a very unconventional job,

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:35.320
[Guest 1]: she is a production controller at Fireworks Films, which does CID and Aahat on Sony.

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:40.200
[Guest 1]: And so she sort of knew that, I mean, she had no idea.

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:42.040
[Guest 1]: She's like, you're going out in the middle of the night, you know,

00:24:42.040 --> 00:24:43.640
[Guest 1]: at nine o'clock in the evening with these notes.

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:45.240
[Guest 1]: And then you're coming back, you're saying, I'll go into a club.

00:24:45.240 --> 00:24:46.920
[Unknown]: And then you're coming back and you're sober.

00:24:46.920 --> 00:24:49.400
[Unknown]: And you have more notes in your hand. What is going on?

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:50.920
[Unknown]: What are you doing in these clubs?

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:55.560
[Guest 1]: But she sort of, and as I was telling Amit, for the first three years,

00:24:55.560 --> 00:24:57.240
[Guest 1]: it was just a labor of love.

00:24:57.240 --> 00:25:01.640
[Guest 1]: We were doing stand up comedy for like garlic bread and a glass Pepsi and all was our payment.

00:25:01.640 --> 00:25:05.080
[Guest 1]: Okay. They sort of stuck with me through it.

00:25:05.080 --> 00:25:11.400
[Guest 1]: And I realized that that deadly combination of two people who have that unending faith

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:16.840
[Guest 1]: and trust in you is what propelled me personally, for sure.

00:25:16.840 --> 00:25:21.080
[Guest 1]: If they had not had, if they were not supportive, I would not be doing this.

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:23.720
[Amit Varma]: So, a shout out to Mrs. Mithil and thank you so much.

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:27.720
[Amit Varma]: So the question here is that how did they then look upon your comedy per se,

00:25:27.720 --> 00:25:32.920
[Amit Varma]: because the kind of comedy that you did and it was very different from what we'll talk about soon,

00:25:32.920 --> 00:25:37.160
[Amit Varma]: which is the kind of comedy that otherwise existed in India before that.

00:25:37.160 --> 00:25:41.160
[Amit Varma]: Worlds apart where you're essentially mining the personal for, you know,

00:25:41.160 --> 00:25:45.240
[Amit Varma]: for using those insights and making people laugh.

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:46.600
[Amit Varma]: How did they react to that?

00:25:46.600 --> 00:25:47.960
[Guest 1]: I think they were thrilled.

00:25:47.960 --> 00:25:50.280
[Guest 1]: I think, like, dad was personally thrilled.

00:25:50.280 --> 00:25:50.920
[Guest 1]: He just...

00:25:50.920 --> 00:25:56.120
[Amit Varma]: But thrilled at the response that, oh, Beti Stage pe hai, or also did they enjoy the form?

00:25:56.920 --> 00:26:00.360
[Guest 1]: Oh, I used to read out everything to my dad.

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:03.000
[Guest 1]: Every line that I, like, if I wrote something new, I would be like,

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:07.000
[Guest 1]: and then he would do the like,

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:11.640
[Amit Varma]: Great, beta, great.

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:12.920
[Amit Varma]: I wish this bit was in video.

00:26:14.600 --> 00:26:16.840
[Guest 1]: It's just like, Fittemu, yeh ladki kya kar rahi hai?

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:19.800
[Guest 1]: Nahi, nahi, great, great, beta, fantastic, fantastic.

00:26:19.800 --> 00:26:25.080
[Guest 1]: So it was sort of like, and I've realized that reaction actually was also very similar to what

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:28.920
[Guest 1]: I used to get on stage in the beginning, is sometimes I used to hear when,

00:26:28.920 --> 00:26:31.640
[Guest 1]: and because the audience is in the dark, right, when you're on stage, I used to hear the...

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:34.760
[Guest 1]: And I used to wonder, like, people don't like it.

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:35.480
[Unknown]: Like, should I stop?

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:36.360
[Unknown]: And it's your daddy.

00:26:42.360 --> 00:26:45.320
[Guest 1]: But I realized it also came from the fact that they were sometimes

00:26:45.320 --> 00:26:50.040
[Guest 1]: titch-titching at themselves for laughing at something that they thought was inappropriate.

00:26:50.840 --> 00:26:54.680
[Guest 1]: So if you're talking about, say, sanitary napkins or Eve teasing or, you know,

00:26:54.680 --> 00:26:58.040
[Guest 1]: penis enlargement cream, they would find it funny,

00:26:58.040 --> 00:27:00.360
[Guest 1]: but they would be shocked that they're laughing at it themselves.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And would they be shocked at what the story says about them?

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Because they're in the story.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.320
[Guest 1]: Oh, no, they are too secure for that.

00:27:07.320 --> 00:27:08.600
[Guest 1]: It's embarrassing.

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:10.920
[Guest 1]: It's embarrassing how they don't care.

00:27:10.920 --> 00:27:13.800
[Guest 1]: Like, my market value at home is zero.

00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:16.520
[Guest 1]: My mother was just like, why do they pay you for this

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:18.280
[Guest 1]: when you're doing this nonsense for free at home?

00:27:19.160 --> 00:27:20.520
[Guest 1]: And I'm like, eh, eh, eh, eh.

00:27:20.520 --> 00:27:21.560
[Amit Varma]: Got lucky.

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:23.640
[Guest 2]: I think that would be almost every comic.

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:25.400
[Guest 2]: I don't think they're very appreciated at home,

00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:28.360
[Guest 2]: which is why they go out and make a film of themselves on stage.

00:27:28.360 --> 00:27:29.400
[Amit Varma]: Look, look for...

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:31.400
[Amit Varma]: But it's probably comics of this generation,

00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:33.640
[Amit Varma]: because we are passing through that transitional phase

00:27:33.640 --> 00:27:36.520
[Amit Varma]: where the older generation is like, not 20 years older than you,

00:27:36.520 --> 00:27:39.240
[Guest 2]: but mentally maybe a century older than you, right?

00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:43.160
[Guest 2]: Yes. Also, like you said, the form previously was different.

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:46.200
[Guest 2]: It was different than what has been happening the last 10 years or so,

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:53.640
[Guest 2]: where mimicry or doing a bit on stage was its own thing,

00:27:53.640 --> 00:27:56.760
[Guest 2]: rather than expressing your opinions or talking about issues,

00:27:57.720 --> 00:28:01.160
[Guest 2]: which is what's been happening in the last decade or so

00:28:01.160 --> 00:28:02.440
[Guest 2]: in Indian stand-up comedy.

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:07.320
[Guest 1]: You know, yeah, and that actually was very dependent

00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:10.280
[Guest 1]: on the method of disbursement of said comedy.

00:28:10.280 --> 00:28:13.720
[Guest 1]: Because most of the comedy that was coming to us prior to the 10 years

00:28:13.720 --> 00:28:17.080
[Guest 1]: was sort of this mainstream mass.

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:17.880
[Unknown]: Exactly.

00:28:17.880 --> 00:28:20.200
[Guest 1]: And so it had to be beamed out to a lot of people

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:21.800
[Guest 1]: and be inoffensive to a lot of people.

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:24.360
[Guest 1]: And so it would catch the lowest common denominator.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:27.400
[Guest 1]: And in most cases, that would be misogynistic, classist, casteist.

00:28:27.400 --> 00:28:30.600
[Amit Varma]: Or even conceptions of what the lowest common denominator is,

00:28:30.600 --> 00:28:33.480
[Amit Varma]: which you probably might not have had any way of testing.

00:28:34.440 --> 00:28:37.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, in the sense that you had a vision of

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:38.760
[Amit Varma]: this is what the people want,

00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:40.280
[Amit Varma]: but do the people really want it?

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:42.920
[Amit Varma]: And you don't really know that because there's no way to test that.

00:28:42.920 --> 00:28:46.840
[Amit Varma]: So those preconceived notions just get pushed further and further.

00:28:46.840 --> 00:28:47.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah, yeah.

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:51.640
[Guest 1]: I mean, till of course, the era of feedback, which is 10 years ago.

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:55.480
[Guest 1]: And I think that's why the stand-up comedy industry,

00:28:55.480 --> 00:29:00.040
[Guest 1]: as I think we are experiencing it, Abbas and I are experiencing it,

00:29:02.040 --> 00:29:05.240
[Guest 1]: is looked at with that much disdain or with that much awe,

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:09.960
[Guest 1]: because it suddenly has a very deeply personal opinion attached to it,

00:29:09.960 --> 00:29:11.320
[Guest 1]: which was not the case before.

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:14.760
[Guest 1]: And so now suddenly you're like, oh, comedians are upstarts and they're,

00:29:14.760 --> 00:29:16.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, abusive losers.

00:29:16.760 --> 00:29:20.840
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps because people feel outraged at their conventional views of the world being challenged.

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:23.640
[Amit Varma]: Because earlier, earlier comedians were entertainers.

00:29:23.640 --> 00:29:28.440
[Amit Varma]: Ki aao, maza karo, slapstick karo, we want to laugh, fall down in a funny way.

00:29:28.440 --> 00:29:31.080
[Amit Varma]: But now they are the voice of society in a sense.

00:29:31.080 --> 00:29:35.320
[Amit Varma]: And people who are sort of find themselves targets of that.

00:29:36.040 --> 00:29:36.840
[Guest 2]: I agree with that.

00:29:36.840 --> 00:29:40.440
[Guest 2]: I would also like to add to when the comedy scene started,

00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:42.360
[Guest 2]: the comedy scene that we are part of.

00:29:42.920 --> 00:29:46.600
[Guest 2]: 10 years ago, it was primarily English comedy and Hindi comedy.

00:29:46.600 --> 00:29:50.680
[Guest 2]: So your Hindi comedy would be looked upon like the Masi kind of thing.

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:55.800
[Guest 2]: Now what's happening is this opinionated comedy about social issues is also happening in Hindi.

00:29:55.800 --> 00:30:00.200
[Guest 2]: A lot of comics from Delhi and the North, or even Mumbai comics

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:02.600
[Guest 2]: are doing that kind of comedy in Hindi also.

00:30:02.600 --> 00:30:05.480
[Guest 2]: So now it's reaching out to that Masi crowd,

00:30:05.480 --> 00:30:09.800
[Guest 2]: but with opinions and thought and well-crafted jokes.

00:30:09.800 --> 00:30:13.240
[Guest 2]: So now that change is coming because more people understand it,

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:15.800
[Guest 2]: more people conceive it, more people demand for it.

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:20.440
[Guest 2]: So I think that's where the crowd is growing more and more for comedy.

00:30:20.440 --> 00:30:26.120
[Guest 2]: And that change is coming and that old guard versus new guard sort of friction exists.

00:30:26.120 --> 00:30:27.560
[Guest 2]: But that's where it is now.

00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:28.920
[Guest 2]: And it'll be interesting to see how.

00:30:28.920 --> 00:30:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Great point. And that's something Aditi brought up earlier when I was telling her about how,

00:30:32.280 --> 00:30:35.240
[Amit Varma]: when I first, like I, in the nineties, I used to,

00:30:35.240 --> 00:30:37.320
[Amit Varma]: I've written for Javed Jaffrey's Time X Time Pass.

00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:38.760
[Amit Varma]: And I also wrote for Cyrus Brochure.

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:44.040
[Amit Varma]: And the predominant notion of comedy then was puns and slapstick and the cheapest form of humor.

00:30:44.040 --> 00:30:47.720
[Amit Varma]: And when standup comedy first started coming to India in the early 2000s,

00:30:47.720 --> 00:30:52.680
[Amit Varma]: I had a very low opinion of it because it was done by these privileged kids with accents.

00:30:52.680 --> 00:30:57.320
[Amit Varma]: And it was very derivative of American standup comedy and not rooted in any way to the

00:30:57.320 --> 00:30:59.960
[Amit Varma]: Indian experience, people like Ash Chandler and so on.

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:02.520
[Guest 2]: And I used to think that was the first name drop has happened.

00:31:03.400 --> 00:31:07.720
[Amit Varma]: And then I sort of went into a cave for five years around to 2009 for various reasons.

00:31:07.720 --> 00:31:10.360
[Amit Varma]: I won't go into, but when I came out of the cave, I suddenly found that,

00:31:10.360 --> 00:31:13.400
[Amit Varma]: my God, there is this explosion of talent all around me.

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:16.200
[Amit Varma]: And you have some genuinely good standup comedy.

00:31:16.200 --> 00:31:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And even if a lot of these people are doing it in English,

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.960
[Amit Varma]: they are still speaking about this no longer so derivative.

00:31:21.960 --> 00:31:22.760
[Amit Varma]: Exactly. Yeah.

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:24.280
[Amit Varma]: How did that happen? What was that process?

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:29.960
[Guest 1]: You know, and so the history of standup comedy, and I, you know, if I may sort of do a like a

00:31:29.960 --> 00:31:33.960
[Guest 1]: quick this thing on the different kinds of comedy, right, the genre is comedy.

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:39.320
[Guest 1]: The methods of practicing it are, you know, one, there is sketch comedy,

00:31:39.320 --> 00:31:42.520
[Guest 1]: which is little sketches, characters, you put them in a little scene.

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:46.280
[Guest 1]: A good example of that would be the flop show, which we all know,

00:31:46.280 --> 00:31:51.400
[Guest 1]: Jaspal Bhatti's show, a flop show where you put a character in a situation and he

00:31:51.400 --> 00:31:55.720
[Guest 1]: overcomes it. And that is where the comedy or tries to overcome it. And that is where the comedy is.

00:31:55.720 --> 00:32:00.520
[Guest 1]: The other one is say improv, which has only come to India in the past sort of

00:32:00.520 --> 00:32:06.280
[Guest 1]: two, three years, even I would say, is where, you know, four players come on stage,

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:11.400
[Guest 1]: you tell them, Arre, name, Pooja, you know, favorite place of Pooja, beach, okay.

00:32:11.400 --> 00:32:15.240
[Guest 1]: Pooja on the beach is enjoying the sunshine. Improv.

00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:21.800
[Guest 1]: Right. And then there is stand up. And the difference, I think, in stand up and the

00:32:21.800 --> 00:32:27.960
[Guest 1]: other forms is that stand up is very pure. It's very like you think the thought,

00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:33.560
[Guest 1]: you write the thought, you perform the thought. It's all you. So when the bookies or the brick

00:32:33.560 --> 00:32:38.360
[Amit Varma]: paths come, they are all you. So as a comedian, as auteur, in a sense,

00:32:38.360 --> 00:32:42.280
[Amit Varma]: where everything is you, you're the director, producer, whatever of the thought.

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:45.320
[Unknown]: Auteurs do. Auteurs as in not otters.

00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:47.320
[Guest 2]: I was like, you thought my pronunciation is very...

00:32:47.320 --> 00:32:49.320
[Unknown]: I was like, this conversation...

00:32:49.320 --> 00:32:51.320
[Unknown]: Auteurs.

00:32:51.320 --> 00:32:53.320
[Unknown]: Auteurs, what have you done?

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:59.320
[Amit Varma]: Now I'm imagining an auteur doing stand up comedy and it's still in use.

00:32:59.320 --> 00:33:01.320
[Amit Varma]: How do you spell it? A-U-T-E-U-R.

00:33:01.320 --> 00:33:03.320
[Guest 2]: Yeah, auteur.

00:33:03.320 --> 00:33:05.320
[Guest 2]: It's not bad either.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:07.320
[Amit Varma]: The Stanley Kubrick kind.

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:09.320
[Guest 1]: We left to such a pretty...

00:33:09.320 --> 00:33:13.320
[Unknown]: Yeah, so I guess, yeah.

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:17.320
[Guest 1]: There is a sense of...

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:23.320
[Guest 1]: Because the origins of stand up comedy also, like abroad, was...

00:33:23.320 --> 00:33:33.320
[Guest 1]: Stand up comedy was sort of the response of the working class to the man, to the society.

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:41.320
[Guest 1]: It is very simple in that it requires no set construction. It requires no sort of fancy lights, big stage.

00:33:41.320 --> 00:33:45.320
[Guest 1]: All you need is a microphone and a person.

00:33:45.320 --> 00:33:51.320
[Guest 1]: So anyone who is anyone, without access to the systems that normally propel you into the entertainment industry,

00:33:51.320 --> 00:33:53.320
[Guest 1]: can come and do stand up.

00:33:53.320 --> 00:34:01.320
[Guest 1]: And that is why it was fiercely independent and I think fiercely anti-establishment for a very long time.

00:34:01.320 --> 00:34:05.320
[Guest 1]: In India, we had what was called Haasiya Kavi Sammelans.

00:34:05.320 --> 00:34:11.320
[Guest 1]: Which would be, you know, just groups of poets sitting around on gaddas and then a microphone in the centre.

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:13.320
[Unknown]: Usually all men.

00:34:13.320 --> 00:34:23.320
[Guest 1]: 99% of the time, all men, sitting around on gaddas and then, you know, one by one coming out to say funny things or tell a funny poem or a story.

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:25.320
[Guest 1]: So we had that happen for a while.

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:34.320
[Guest 1]: It caught the public imagination like nothing else in 2001 with the launch of the first Great Indian Laughter Challenge.

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:42.320
[Guest 1]: That first season, comedy in all its iterations of making statements on society and stuff had existed in our theatre.

00:34:42.320 --> 00:34:51.320
[Guest 1]: And on a local level, I mean, we have the funny bits of Ramlila that would sort of stand out always, you know, during Diwali celebrations also.

00:34:51.320 --> 00:34:54.320
[Guest 1]: So we had those small, small things happening.

00:34:54.320 --> 00:35:00.320
[Guest 1]: 2001, when Great Indian Laughter Challenge hit our TV screens and lasted, I think, 13 seasons.

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:01.320
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

00:35:01.320 --> 00:35:06.320
[Guest 1]: It revolutionised the way we saw comedy.

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:11.320
[Guest 1]: The problem was, of course, then it fell back into the same trap of catering to the lowest common denominator.

00:35:11.320 --> 00:35:17.320
[Guest 2]: I was just about to say that most of the stuff was derivative and sexist and, you know, not very quality wise.

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:25.320
[Amit Varma]: Did you see the shift that happened, happened that earlier, the funny guy in a Bollywood movie, for example, was someone you laughed at who was behaving like a clown or whatever.

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:30.320
[Amit Varma]: And that changed and instead it became something else.

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:37.320
[Guest 2]: I think Bollywood wise, I think we're still a long way to go to capture good comedy on screen that way.

00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:42.320
[Guest 1]: But you know, sorry, sorry, may I interrupt with Johnny bhai's, I call him Johnny bhai, like he's a friend of mine.

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:52.320
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, I'm like, I'm in awe. But then I'll meet him a week later and I'll be like Johnny bhai, I did a podcast with Aditi and he'll be like, Kaun, kaun re bhai.

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:57.320
[Guest 1]: But his origins were, I mean, he's called Johnny Lever because he worked with Hindustan Lever.

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:06.320
[Guest 1]: And one of the things that they did was during, you know, worker meetings and stuff like that, they would be like, aarey koi entertainment karne ko jao, Johnny bhai kuch toh bolo.

00:36:06.320 --> 00:36:13.320
[Guest 1]: And Johnny bhai, so Johnny bhai found his footing as a comedian doing stand up comedy.

00:36:13.320 --> 00:36:19.320
[Guest 1]: Single man behind a microphone, just pulled out from the audience, tell a story and make everyone laugh.

00:36:19.320 --> 00:36:27.320
[Guest 1]: He then moved on. And I think that's what's happening to us also as an industry is even though we might be speaking in the language of what is the urban elite in English,

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:38.320
[Guest 1]: because we exist in Bombay, we are being co-opted into the Bollywood entertainment industry. You know, there's, you will see often see comedians collaborating with, you know,

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:44.320
[Guest 1]: filmmakers or production houses to either promote a film or to, you know, be in a film or to write dialogue for a film.

00:36:44.320 --> 00:36:49.320
[Guest 1]: So that I think, like that is just a sort of a natural progression.

