[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the Unseen. I'm here with Aditi Mittal and Abbas Momin. We're talking about the history of stand-up comedy in India.

00:37:58.320 --> 00:38:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And Aditi, so my next question to you is, and Abbas, tell us about your experiences in this also.

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:08.320
[Amit Varma]: When did you first figure out that you wanted to do stand-up comedy?

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:14.320
[Amit Varma]: When did it actually strike you that rather than just make wisecracks in front of the class, I want to actually go on a stage and do this?

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:22.320
[Guest 1]: You know, I went to an open mic and I was watching some slam poetry happen. And I was like, I can do this.

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:28.320
[Guest 1]: Around which year was this? 2010. And I saw this and I was like, oh, I can do this.

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:39.320
[Guest 1]: And then the next, literally the next week was a stand-up comedy open mic. And the thing is, when I was in college, and I was in college in the US, you know, I had watched a bunch of stand-up comedy.

00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:46.320
[Guest 1]: I used to go to clubs all the time because they would have these $5 nights where you just paid $5 and you would get to watch like three shows back to back.

00:38:46.320 --> 00:38:55.320
[Guest 1]: And I had nothing to do. So I used to sit and watch these like, like hour long shows of just comedians who knew who would just come and do these hour long sets.

00:38:55.320 --> 00:38:59.320
[Guest 1]: And so when I moved to India, I saw this. I said, I got to try this.

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:02.320
[Amit Varma]: And who were the guys you liked? Who were the guys you could relate to?

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:06.320
[Guest 1]: At that point in time, really? Nobody. Nobody.

00:39:06.320 --> 00:39:15.320
[Guest 1]: And I don't mean here. I mean, there. Oh, there. If I say it right now, I will be like, I don't because I don't believe I don't, I'm not inspired by that person anymore.

00:39:15.320 --> 00:39:24.320
[Unknown]: Louis CK. No, no, no. Bill Cosby. Bill Maher. I was like, what a guy he is. What a way to talk. Wow.

00:39:24.320 --> 00:39:32.320
[Unknown]: And I mean, clearly my thoughts have changed. The tone has changed. What a guy he is. It's become that. That's right.

00:39:32.320 --> 00:39:42.320
[Guest 1]: But at that point, I sort of, I was really taken in by the ability to speak again, truth to power and to do it as simply and directly as you can.

00:39:42.320 --> 00:39:53.320
[Guest 1]: And I think one of the things I was confused about was the fact that Hindi and the way we speak in India, like it's a very euphemistic language.

00:39:53.320 --> 00:40:06.320
[Guest 1]: It's there's a lot of ways. You know, most of the most simple, direct ideas will sometimes find a veneer and covering of 3000 different kinds of phrases.

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:13.320
[Guest 1]: And that becomes exhausting just to even process it while listening to it. And I remember that was my first impulse with stand up.

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:17.320
[Guest 1]: I was like, just go say it directly. Just go say it directly and see what effect it has.

00:40:17.320 --> 00:40:23.320
[Guest 1]: Because it's not like the whole world is not talking about these things already or someone is not saying these things already.

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:28.320
[Guest 1]: But just go say it directly and see what sort of the feedback that comes to you.

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:36.320
[Guest 1]: And so I remember my first set was, again, trying to process tragedy was I, you know, I've always been a slightly chubby person.

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:44.320
[Guest 1]: And I said, I went on stage and I talked about how, you know, when fat guys, you know, when whenever friends,

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:48.320
[Guest 1]: if a friend is hooking you up with a fat guy, should always be like, oh, my God, you know, you know, he's amazing.

00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:52.320
[Guest 1]: He has a heart of gold or he's amazing. He's like a teddy bear or whatever.

00:40:52.320 --> 00:40:57.320
[Guest 1]: But there were no euphemisms for fat girls. There was nothing that was like, oh, she's amazing.

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:04.320
[Guest 1]: But, you know, she's also slightly sweaty all the time. Those things are not.

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:12.320
[Guest 1]: And so I went and did this set and it got two laughs. It wasn't great. It wasn't like, oh, my God, they carried me off on their shoulders and signed me up for a Hollywood movie immediately.

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:21.320
[Guest 1]: But I think that was that one moment when I realized I can get laughs. Then it just became a pursuit of laughs.

00:41:21.320 --> 00:41:25.320
[Guest 1]: There was no there was no time consciously that I was like, oh, I want to do this.

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:29.320
[Amit Varma]: And once you start doing it, does it change the way you sort of think about the world?

00:41:29.320 --> 00:41:32.320
[Amit Varma]: Like, are you then processing everything through? Can this be part of my material?

00:41:32.320 --> 00:41:37.320
[Guest 1]: I think, yes, I am almost like I have now started putting pressure on myself.

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:43.320
[Guest 1]: I can't believe this. But at the age of 32, I'm one of those people that says I want to live.

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:47.320
[Unknown]: My mother's like, dude, what are 90? And I'm like, no, no, I want to live.

00:41:47.320 --> 00:41:56.320
[Guest 1]: I want to experience life because I think one of the things that stand up does is or comedy does is it makes you want to live life.

00:41:56.320 --> 00:42:01.320
[Guest 1]: So you can filter those experiences through the lens of comedy.

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:08.320
[Guest 1]: So I've just I've pushed myself into tons of uncomfortable situations just because I'm like material.

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:17.320
[Guest 1]: I've done corporate shows like I went for this one corporate show where I got asked if I wanted to be because I mean, initially when they called me,

00:42:17.320 --> 00:42:21.320
[Guest 1]: they were like, oh, you know, like you're so bold and open minded and we love how bold and open minded you are.

00:42:21.320 --> 00:42:27.320
[Guest 1]: And I should have picked up on the fact that they were really honing in on the fact that I was bold and open minded.

00:42:27.320 --> 00:42:29.320
[Amit Varma]: So they wanted that or they were warning you against it?

00:42:29.320 --> 00:42:31.320
[Guest 1]: No, no, they were like, no, we love it. We love it.

00:42:31.320 --> 00:42:37.320
[Guest 1]: So I went into this, I do this like fairly bold and open minded set and then I come out and then they invited me into a threesome.

00:42:37.320 --> 00:42:45.320
[Guest 1]: And I was like, oh, you know, I don't know if my bold and open mind extends to my bold and open sex life.

00:42:45.320 --> 00:42:50.320
[Guest 2]: But it happens at corporate shows. I've been saying no to all corporate shows.

00:42:50.320 --> 00:43:02.320
[Amit Varma]: So when did you start performing?

00:43:02.320 --> 00:43:09.320
[Guest 2]: I went to my first open mic in 2012. And I only realized that I wanted to do it when I did my first open mic.

00:43:09.320 --> 00:43:10.320
[Unknown]: Why did you do it?

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:14.320
[Guest 2]: Because I was scared. I was very introvert. I didn't have the courage to go on stage.

00:43:14.320 --> 00:43:24.320
[Guest 2]: And the first time I did it also happened by accident because I took this workshop, stand up comedy writing workshop by the then very newly formed East India Comedy.

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:31.320
[Guest 2]: And I went under the pretense that they're going to tell us how to write material and I'll write it and someday I will go on stage and try it.

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:38.320
[Guest 2]: But when I reached there, I found out so the afternoon was the workshop and that same night you had to perform the material.

00:43:38.320 --> 00:43:45.320
[Guest 2]: So we had two minutes on stage, I think 12 or 14 of us and we had to write two minutes of material and do it on stage.

00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:50.320
[Guest 2]: And my two minutes of material I just dropped out of dentistry back then and come back to Bombay.

00:43:50.320 --> 00:43:57.320
[Guest 2]: So my two minutes were mostly about how I'm fat, how I'm balding at a young age and how I quit dentistry and disappointed my dad.

00:43:57.320 --> 00:44:00.320
[Guest 2]: And people lost their shit. They were laughing their ass off.

00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:07.320
[Guest 2]: And I thought, wait a minute, if I tell you about the problems and troubles of my life, you find it funny. Maybe I can do this.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:09.320
[Unknown]: So that's that was the first thing.

00:44:09.320 --> 00:44:14.320
[Amit Varma]: So you were used in your in your previous profession, you would cause pain to people and now you were making them laugh.

00:44:14.320 --> 00:44:27.320
[Unknown]: Comedy is a way of dispelling tension. I can imagine the stand up dentist where he's got his tools and all over the person's face and he's telling him a joke, which is out of personal material.

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:30.320
[Unknown]: Do you know a patient died at my chair?

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:39.320
[Guest 2]: Obviously, the build up to that, of course, was I was a comedy fan before I ever tried it.

00:44:39.320 --> 00:44:43.320
[Guest 2]: So the comedy store, which is now the Canvas Laugh Club had opened newly back then.

00:44:43.320 --> 00:44:48.320
[Guest 2]: And Aditi and all of these guys used to perform. I used to be almost there every week.

00:44:48.320 --> 00:44:51.320
[Guest 2]: I couldn't go the weekends because the tickets were a little too expensive.

00:44:51.320 --> 00:44:54.320
[Guest 2]: But they had these local hero nights on Wednesdays and Tuesdays.

00:44:54.320 --> 00:45:00.320
[Guest 2]: So I used to go I used to watch all of them, Abish, Sahil Shah, Rohan Joshi, Tanmay Bhatt, Aditi, all of them.

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:07.320
[Guest 2]: So I became like hardcore fans of them. I would tweet to them. I will I would follow them to find out where they are performing.

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:11.320
[Guest 2]: So so yeah, that's where it came from. And then I wanted to be like them.

00:45:11.320 --> 00:45:15.320
[Guest 2]: So so yeah, that that wanted me to go to open mic nights and perform.

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:20.320
[Guest 2]: So you performed first in 2012. But from when did you start watching and following these people?

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:26.320
[Guest 2]: Around 2009, 10. So I think I was in Bangalore studying dentistry and I wasn't liking it at all.

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:31.320
[Guest 2]: So I used to cut classes. I used to sit at home and just binge watch sitcoms.

00:45:31.320 --> 00:45:35.320
[Guest 2]: And I realized that the writers of these sitcoms are also stand up comics.

00:45:35.320 --> 00:45:38.320
[Guest 2]: So I would YouTube their name and watch their material.

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:40.320
[Amit Varma]: Like like who are the guys?

00:45:40.320 --> 00:45:46.320
[Guest 2]: So there was this writer called Judah Friedlander on 30 Rock. And I would watch him repeatedly.

00:45:46.320 --> 00:45:53.320
[Guest 2]: Then there was this one video that HBO did, which has now become like a cult among comedians.

00:45:53.320 --> 00:46:00.320
[Guest 2]: It was called Talking Funny. It was Chris Rock, Jerry Seinfeld, Ricky Gervais and Louis CK in a room talking about comedy.

00:46:00.320 --> 00:46:05.320
[Guest 2]: Now I knew Chris Rock, I knew Seinfeld, I knew Gervais from the television and movie stuff.

00:46:05.320 --> 00:46:09.320
[Guest 2]: Then I didn't know who Louis CK was. So I googled his name, saw his stand up.

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:15.320
[Guest 2]: And again, this all feels very weird to say is now because Louis CK is now disgraced.

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:22.320
[Guest 2]: But there's one joke that he did, which stuck in my head where he said he was talking about his daughters.

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:29.320
[Guest 2]: He said as a dad, you look for the mini vacations that you take in your life, like you shove your daughters in the car,

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:34.320
[Guest 2]: you close the door and you walk to the driver's side. That's a mini vacation for me.

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:39.320
[Guest 2]: I'm not a dad. I'm not a middle aged man. But I still found that joke so hilarious.

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:46.320
[Guest 2]: And in that one moment, I went back to all the times I saw my dad taking that walk in the car to the driver's side

00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:50.320
[Guest 2]: and thinking what must be going in his mind when that happened.

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:55.320
[Amit Varma]: So you had a good start there for Aditi. The first time you performed, people laughed and it went well.

00:46:55.320 --> 00:46:58.320
[Amit Varma]: Was it always like that in your early days?

00:46:58.320 --> 00:47:06.320
[Guest 1]: No, and it's still not. I think one of the greatest things about this job is that you throw a sheer wall every day and hope it sticks.

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:10.320
[Guest 1]: And you never know if it's going to stick. I know I can, I still do bad shows.

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:13.320
[Guest 1]: I still do shows where I'm like, oh, you know, that could have gone better.

00:47:13.320 --> 00:47:16.320
[Guest 1]: I could have said that, you know, I could have pronounced that clearer.

00:47:16.320 --> 00:47:20.320
[Guest 1]: I could have hit that line more clearly. I could have put that other thought inside.

00:47:20.320 --> 00:47:24.320
[Guest 1]: So I think the unsurety of stand up actually.

00:47:24.320 --> 00:47:28.320
[Amit Varma]: And you ever feel that I did the right thing? I was funny. The audience was stupid. They didn't get it.

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:34.320
[Guest 1]: Very rarely. Very rarely. I mean, I think I'm awed by our audiences.

00:47:34.320 --> 00:47:43.320
[Guest 1]: I think I I've never been anywhere where I've thought that the audience didn't get it because I think empathy is what is required.

00:47:43.320 --> 00:47:49.320
[Guest 1]: Even if you're speaking in a very different language, I think people latch on to your confidence, your energy.

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:56.320
[Guest 1]: And so I've never stood in front of an audience that I feel like it's their fault for not getting me.

00:47:56.320 --> 00:48:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, from those early days of stand up when you started in 2010 to today, and not just a question about your own comedy,

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:11.320
[Amit Varma]: but also the comedy of the others around you. Has it changed much in terms of content, the kind of things you're handling,

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:14.320
[Amit Varma]: or is it just more a sharpening of the craft?

00:48:14.320 --> 00:48:20.320
[Guest 1]: Yes, I think so. Definitely. In fact, I think now we are smarter in that we know that you approach it with stereotypes.

00:48:20.320 --> 00:48:27.320
[Guest 1]: Punjabis are loud. You know, Maharashtrians don't do work. Gujaratis are always eating sweet dal.

00:48:27.320 --> 00:48:33.320
[Amit Varma]: That's not a stereotype I've heard actually. I've heard the cheap tickets Gujarati stereotype.

00:48:33.320 --> 00:48:39.320
[Amit Varma]: Correct. Sorry. That's what I meant. Sugar is poison anyway.

00:48:39.320 --> 00:48:42.320
[Guest 1]: But you start with the stereotypes because those are accessible.

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:48.320
[Guest 1]: Those you are sort of gathering in as many people as you can on those and then you take them on your personal journey.

00:48:48.320 --> 00:48:55.320
[Guest 1]: Then you say, oh, and by the way, you know, the other day I was thinking about death and this is after sweet dal.

00:48:55.320 --> 00:49:00.320
[Guest 1]: Sweet dal, death. And that's how you sort of take them on your journey.

00:49:00.320 --> 00:49:06.320
[Guest 1]: I think, you know, audiences that way are very open, are extremely open.

00:49:06.320 --> 00:49:16.320
[Guest 1]: I've performed abroad for Indian audiences and I've realized that Indian audiences abroad are more conservative than Indian audiences in India.

00:49:16.320 --> 00:49:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And they vote more for the BJP. So why? That's not supposed to be funny.

00:49:21.320 --> 00:49:26.320
[Guest 2]: The two aren't connected or are they? No, but I mean, because they're stuck in whatever year they left.

00:49:26.320 --> 00:49:33.320
[Guest 1]: So if they like, I remember, last year I was in London and somebody was doing a song.

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:38.320
[Guest 1]: Somebody was dancing to some function and cultural function was dancing to Chane Ke Khetme.

00:49:38.320 --> 00:49:45.320
[Guest 1]: Y'all that is a 1997 song. But this person, clearly her parents left when they were in 1997.

00:49:45.320 --> 00:49:50.320
[Guest 1]: And so this 12, 14 year old girl is dancing to Chane Ke Khetme like it was released yesterday.

00:49:50.320 --> 00:49:58.320
[Guest 1]: So I think they're still stuck in the time that they left the country with that same notion of like, you know, what India was and they carry that there.

00:49:58.320 --> 00:50:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And we were discussing earlier about how, you know, English speaking people like us tend to be in this small cocoon,

00:50:03.320 --> 00:50:07.320
[Amit Varma]: which of course, because niches are so big in India is a fairly big cocoon in absolute numbers.

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:17.320
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it's just a small niche and there's a danger in sort of the selection bias where you imagine that these 200 people who are coming to my shows are the audience.

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:26.320
[Amit Varma]: And there's really, you know, not much beyond that. Is that something you think about in the sense of how has the audience for stand up comedy evolved in India?

00:50:26.320 --> 00:50:30.320
[Amit Varma]: Is it really growing? What kind of comedy are there? How are the tastes changing?

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:39.320
[Guest 2]: Well, how are the tastes changing? Like I made the earlier point about the language, what was seen as a language barrier that these are English comedians,

00:50:39.320 --> 00:50:49.320
[Guest 2]: they do the high fun do stuff, they speak to an elite audience that is breaking down as we go. That's primarily because of the internet and the streaming websites,

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:59.320
[Guest 2]: where comedy is one of the top genres, right? See any YouTube video, stand up comedy video, it'll easily have around a million views.

00:50:59.320 --> 00:51:07.320
[Guest 2]: So I think comedians use the language of the people to make relevant points, the more the mindset of the people will expand,

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:18.320
[Guest 2]: and the more accepting they will be, right? You have comedians doing English comedy, you have comedians down south, doing comedy in Tamil and English.

00:51:18.320 --> 00:51:26.320
[Guest 2]: So that barrier of this is only for the elite crowd and the rest of them will be excluded out. That's, that's kind of changing now.

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:32.320
[Guest 2]: So I think that's gonna, that's gonna be the turning point where language won't be a barrier anymore.

00:51:32.320 --> 00:51:39.320
[Guest 2]: The kind of comedy that English comedians did when it starts going out to more people, more people will be accepting of it.

00:51:39.320 --> 00:51:47.320
[Guest 2]: Or if they're not accepting of it, at least I hope it will force them to think and know that there is this alternate thought process out there.

00:51:47.320 --> 00:51:57.320
[Guest 2]: And if we expose ourselves to that, the world won't end. It's okay to expose yourself to different kinds of thought processes and mindsets and points of views.

00:51:57.320 --> 00:52:06.320
[Guest 2]: So ideally, comedy should be for all points of views. And then you pick and choose and find your sort of what you like.

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:14.320
[Amit Varma]: And in these kinds of polarizing times, and comedians are always sort of speaking truth to power and just going out there fearlessly.

00:52:14.320 --> 00:52:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And in these kinds of polarizing times, do you find yourself self censoring or thinking, I mean, what kind of pushback do you face?

00:52:21.320 --> 00:52:29.320
[Guest 1]: You know, and so actually, instead of adding to Abbas's point, I personally feel like we're still in the gathering stage.

00:52:29.320 --> 00:52:41.320
[Guest 1]: I think, you know, I mean, we have a 2% repeat audience at say, a canvas laugh club, that means 98% of the people who are coming for a comedy show at any given point in time have never seen comedy before.

00:52:41.320 --> 00:52:48.320
[Guest 1]: And so I think actually, we are still in the phase of the sort of the upward thing of the bell curve.

00:52:48.320 --> 00:52:53.320
[Amit Varma]: And that's actually worrying also, because it means if only 2% are repeat, then there aren't enough repeats.

00:52:53.320 --> 00:53:00.320
[Guest 1]: Because it started with so little. Right. So it's sort of, you know, and I mean, by like one day for the next, right.

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:06.320
[Amit Varma]: So on Monday, or whatever, so some of those 98 maybe repeats from previous day. Correct.

00:53:06.320 --> 00:53:14.320
[Guest 1]: There is a, like, again, the fascination, I know, I've been hired for shows where they've just been like, what is comedy?

00:53:14.320 --> 00:53:19.320
[Guest 1]: Like, wait a minute, you don't know? So why did you call me? But they're just, they just want to know.

00:53:19.320 --> 00:53:24.320
[Guest 1]: They're just curious that how, like, how does this get handled? They'll have the conception that they'll come and abuse everyone.

00:53:24.320 --> 00:53:30.320
[Guest 1]: They will come and call everyone Chitra, Chitra, Chitra, Chitra and f*** off. Which also is a thing that people think.

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:38.320
[Guest 1]: I know that I, you know, I did a show in a smaller city recently, and we had about 900 people show up.

00:53:38.320 --> 00:53:46.320
[Guest 1]: And then the organizer comes up to me and I said, dude, this is crazy. I did not know there were 900 people in this city.

00:53:46.320 --> 00:53:53.320
[Guest 1]: And he's like, dude, no, he's like, you know, about 300 of them, 100% got what you're saying.

00:53:53.320 --> 00:54:00.320
[Guest 1]: But the remaining 600 were just there to see what this was. And I was just sort of blown away by that.

00:54:00.320 --> 00:54:06.320
[Guest 1]: I was like, oh, I did not know that we're still in that. You are literally the first exposure to this.

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:17.320
[Guest 2]: A lot of us in that phase where us being on stage and seeing these things is the first time they're hearing these kind of sentences constructed on stage.

00:54:17.320 --> 00:54:29.320
[Amit Varma]: And what I kind of find is, you know, like, if you look back on the Soviet Union, it was a golden period of humor for them, because the state was so oppressive that the only way you could express your dissent was through humor.

00:54:29.320 --> 00:54:40.320
[Amit Varma]: And the state, of course, never gets satire. So that's just perfect. And in a sense, if you look at what's been happening here over the last two or three years,

00:54:40.320 --> 00:54:49.320
[Amit Varma]: and I don't intend to say for a moment that we're anywhere near that oppressive, but regardless, in these polarized times, especially in terms of cartoons,

00:54:49.320 --> 00:54:56.320
[Amit Varma]: I just find a lot of these cartoonists like Manjul and Sandeep of Times of India and all are just doing mind blowing work.

00:54:56.320 --> 00:55:03.320
[Guest 1]: And actually, I think that is one of the sort of the one of the pillars of comedy in India has been our cartoonists.

00:55:03.320 --> 00:55:15.320
[Guest 1]: Because every eight kilometers, if our language changes, if you know, we have such varied striations of economics, of society, of class, caste, etc, etc,

00:55:15.320 --> 00:55:23.320
[Guest 1]: then surely language can almost be a barrier in understanding each other. That's why you have small groups of offense popping up.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:30.320
[Guest 1]: There's always six people who are suddenly offended at one thing, right? The remaining 350 don't care.

00:55:30.320 --> 00:55:37.320
[Guest 1]: But cartoonists have been able to bridge that gap merely because images.

00:55:37.320 --> 00:55:46.320
[Guest 1]: And of course, I mean, largest distribution networks of newspapers in the world and therefore, you know, the channels of distribution are also extensive.

00:55:46.320 --> 00:56:04.320
[Guest 1]: I think that's why our cartoonist Manjul Toons, to a certain extent, Mr. Hemant Umar Paria, are just doing amazing work and sort of presenting more potent statements on the current state of our government than any comedian ever will be able to with words.

00:56:04.320 --> 00:56:11.320
[Amit Varma]: And I've heard someone make the interesting point about stand up comedy in India that because stand up comedy in the US, for example, has such a long tradition,

00:56:11.320 --> 00:56:20.320
[Amit Varma]: you've got people tackling all the different phases of life through that, whether it's middle age or growing old and death and so on and so forth.

00:56:20.320 --> 00:56:27.320
[Amit Varma]: But in India, it's kind of a young bunch of early pioneers. And therefore, sometimes it might still be a little shallow.

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:34.320
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes they don't go as deep into some of those subjects. And over the years, like, what do you feel about that?

00:56:34.320 --> 00:56:40.320
[Amit Varma]: Like, do you feel that you are becoming a more rounded comedian just by living more and just growing older?

00:56:40.320 --> 00:56:54.320
[Guest 1]: Do you know and so I think the youngness of stand up comedy, the first of all, because it's one of those jobs where you don't make money for three years, you have to be young and stupid and dependent on your parents to be able to like, breathe, eat, live.

00:56:54.320 --> 00:57:15.320
[Guest 1]: Then also, by the way, the economic this thing behind it, I think one of the, in fact, almost what I think has been the downfall of the stand up industry in India is the fact that we are, I mean, one, first of all, the youngest country in the world and are the comedians and especially the comedy groups figured out that the younger you get them,

00:57:15.320 --> 00:57:29.320
[Guest 1]: the longer you will be able to milk that ticket money, you know, into their 20s and into their 30s. And so there has been, I believe, due to the economic incentive, a juvenile ization of our comedy.

00:57:29.320 --> 00:57:30.320
[Amit Varma]: So you mean it's become more juvenile?

00:57:30.320 --> 00:57:36.320
[Guest 1]: You know, it's I mean, it started with juvenile and has, I mean, the economic drive to be juvenile is there.

00:57:36.320 --> 00:57:42.320
[Guest 1]: Because the audience is young and respond to it and because they buy tickets and because it's, you know, edgy.

00:57:42.320 --> 00:57:45.320
[Amit Varma]: So what is a juvenile is what kind of humor does it entail?

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:47.320
[Guest 1]: I mean, I don't want to be specific.

00:57:47.320 --> 00:57:58.320
[Amit Varma]: I don't take names, but like a gag like this, for example, or a move in this direction, for example, or you're joking about X, for example.

00:57:58.320 --> 00:58:13.320
[Guest 2]: Okay, let me try and simplify. I think the thing is, so you catch certain tropes that you know, will get clicks or likes or views.

00:58:13.320 --> 00:58:18.320
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm really struggling. I mean, give me an illustration. I'm not trolling you.

00:58:18.320 --> 00:58:25.320
[Guest 2]: Okay, I mean, put the guy, newbie on the spot.

00:58:25.320 --> 00:58:31.320
[Unknown]: Shall I? Baby, go for it. I am in the background without the mic.

00:58:31.320 --> 00:58:40.320
[Guest 2]: Okay, so for example, let's say, so AIB did something this Valentine's Day called Pyaar Ek Dhoka Hai.

00:58:40.320 --> 00:58:45.320
[Guest 2]: They use that tagline to garner as many people as they can.

00:58:45.320 --> 00:58:51.320
[Guest 2]: And there were a lot of questions raised around that slogan itself, where Pyaar Ek Dhoka Hai, what does it entail?

00:58:51.320 --> 00:59:00.320
[Guest 2]: Is there a reason behind it? Or is there a firm point you're trying to make? Or is it just let's give them a slogan, let's get as many people as we want.

00:59:00.320 --> 00:59:07.320
[Guest 2]: And let's just make this a place where we can get the eyeballs, get more publicity, more subscribers, more.

00:59:07.320 --> 00:59:18.320
[Guest 2]: And many times what happens is comedy groups use, like I said, certain tropes, and then they would use this similar kind of trope in multiple sketches or videos that they make.

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:25.320
[Guest 2]: Which sometimes reeks of, we found a safe spot, comfort spot, and we're going to stay there.

00:59:25.320 --> 00:59:28.320
[Guest 2]: And we know we're going to get eyeballs. So let's not experiment a lot.

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:39.320
[Amit Varma]: So your objection is not to the trope per se, but to the fact that once they find a trope that works with getting reliable eyeballs, you don't push the envelope beyond that.

00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:46.320
[Guest 1]: Yes. That's exactly it, actually. I mean, you know, you're like a 36 year old dude, like you're sitting in like something called Bakcho,

00:59:46.320 --> 00:59:52.320
[Guest 1]: then your shows are called Turdford and all this, like, you know, grow up. You really grow up.

00:59:52.320 --> 00:59:57.320
[Guest 1]: I think it sort of becomes like beyond the point you have to start speaking your age.

00:59:57.320 --> 01:00:05.320
[Guest 1]: And that's what it is, is that nobody's talking about being a 36 year old man, even though there are so many 36 year old men in comedy.

01:00:05.320 --> 01:00:08.320
[Guest 1]: What's happening? Young people from where I stand.

01:00:08.320 --> 01:00:20.320
[Guest 1]: But you know what I'm saying? It's sort of then that becomes confining. It becomes like, you know, even the older men in comedy are being compelled to do jokes about, then they'll do like WhatsApp level jokes.

01:00:20.320 --> 01:00:27.320
[Guest 1]: Because they know, I'll say, if a woman takes a lot of time to wear clothes, she'll get applause.

01:00:27.320 --> 01:00:38.320
[Guest 1]: So, yay, she doesn't know how to park. And so that I think will also then, I mean, as I said, the economic incentive for juvenile is very high.

01:00:38.320 --> 01:00:43.320
[Guest 1]: Having said that, we have to then incentivize a variety of voices.

01:00:43.320 --> 01:00:51.320
[Amit Varma]: And having said that, like one thing you pointed out earlier about when stand up comedy started was that one reason it took off was because it was a pure form.

01:00:51.320 --> 01:00:57.320
[Amit Varma]: There were no entry barriers. Or you needed no equipment, nothing. You could just stand at a town square and do your gig.

01:00:57.320 --> 01:01:02.320
[Amit Varma]: And that is way more true today than ever before, because it just is no entry barrier.

01:01:02.320 --> 01:01:07.320
[Amit Varma]: You can take your mobile phone, shoot a video of yourself, put it on YouTube, or you can go to any open mics anywhere.

01:01:07.320 --> 01:01:18.320
[Amit Varma]: And surely that's a good thing. And even if it means that mainstream tastes are either juvenile or may not agree with them or whatever, there is still space for all kinds of comedy.

01:01:18.320 --> 01:01:21.320
[Amit Varma]: Would you say there's enough of that?

01:01:21.320 --> 01:01:26.320
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I don't think there is enough diversity at all. We don't have any good Dalit comics. We barely have like 10-15 female comics.

01:01:26.320 --> 01:01:33.320
[Guest 1]: We have three gay comics. We have, I mean, the variety of perspectives is so little.

01:01:33.320 --> 01:01:37.320
[Amit Varma]: So we'll discuss misogyny in the entertainment industry in the next episode.

01:01:37.320 --> 01:01:46.320
[Amit Varma]: But I nevertheless want to ask you now that why is it that there is so little diversity? Is it only access or are there structural reasons behind it?

01:01:46.320 --> 01:01:51.320
[Guest 1]: There is access, of course. I mean, you know, to enter one of these clubs, you have to be able to enter a mall.

01:01:51.320 --> 01:01:56.320
[Guest 1]: I mean, to be able to enter a mall, you need to look a certain way without the security stopping you.

01:01:56.320 --> 01:02:04.320
[Guest 1]: You know, you get in there and I mean, I like I am sort of the top of the top of the top of the pile when it comes to having privilege.

